SIMPLE: phrase
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Phrase
<hw>Phrase</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>phrasis</ets> diction, phraseology, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ to
speak.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A brief expression, sometimes a single
word, but usually two or more words forming an expression by themselves,
or being a portion of a sentence; <as>as, an adverbial
<ex>phrase</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>⟦ldquo⟧Convey⟦rdquo⟧ the wise it call. ⟦ldquo⟧Steal!⟦rdquo⟧ foh! a
fico for the <qex>phrase</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A short, pithy expression; especially, one which is
often employed; a peculiar or idiomatic turn of speech; <as>as, <ex>to
err is human</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A mode or form of speech; the manner or style in
which any one expreses himself; diction; expression.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Phrases</xex> of the hearth.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou speak'st⟦br⟧
In better <qex>phrase</qex> and matter than thou didst.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A short clause or portion of a
period.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ A composition consists first of sentences, or
<xex>periods</xex>; these are subdivided into <xex>sections</xex>, and
these into <xex>phrases</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Phrase book</b></col>, <cd>a book of idiomatic
phrases.</cd> <rj><au>J. S. Blackie.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Phrase</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Phrase
<hw>Phrase</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Phrased</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Phrasing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>phraser</ets>.]</ety> <def>To express in words, or in peculiar
words; to call; to style.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧These suns -- for so they
<xex>phrase</xex> 'em.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Phrase</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Phrase
<hw>Phrase</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To use proper or fine
phrases.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To group notes into phrases;
<as>as, he <ex>phrases</ex> well</as>. See <er>Phrase</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 4.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Phraseless</ent>⟦br⟧
